00:28:18.640 --> 00:28:19.640
&gt;&gt;Reto: Yeah.

00:28:19.640 --> 00:28:20.640
Absolutely.

00:28:20.640 --> 00:28:21.640
&gt;&gt;Ian: -that the new system gives you.

00:28:21.640 --> 00:28:22.640
&gt;&gt;Reto: Yeah.

00:28:22.640 --> 00:28:27.140
&gt;&gt;Ian: Now for this, you know maybe they've
got some really cool camera stuff going on.

00:28:27.140 --> 00:28:35.540
The problem is that a lot of the coolest camera
technology in Android is being supplied by

00:28:35.540 --> 00:28:43.660
OEM libraries so, you may be missing out on
something really, really slick if you completely

00:28:43.660 --> 00:28:44.660
override the camera.

00:28:44.660 --> 00:28:47.429
&gt;&gt;Reto: That's interesting, if I hit front
facing it doesn't do anything.

00:28:47.429 --> 00:28:50.010
So, it may be a bug.

00:28:50.010 --> 00:28:52.320
&gt;&gt;Ian: Well, that's what you get right?

00:28:52.320 --> 00:28:53.600
&gt;&gt;Reto: It's certainly freezing.

00:28:53.600 --> 00:28:56.410
&gt;&gt;Ian: Did it just freeze, you think?

00:28:56.410 --> 00:28:57.410
&gt;&gt;Reto: No, it's back.

00:28:57.410 --> 00:28:58.410
&gt;&gt;Ian: OK

00:28:58.410 --> 00:28:59.410
&gt;&gt;Reto: It seems to just take a while.

00:28:59.410 --> 00:29:03.580
&gt;&gt;Ian: So the only reason I can think of that
you'd want to build a custom camera and do

00:29:03.580 --> 00:29:09.580
the preview yourself is if you really need
to do live preview.

00:29:09.580 --> 00:29:11.250
So do these guys do live preview?

00:29:11.250 --> 00:29:14.600
&gt;&gt;Reto: I believe that they do, yeah if you
hit the- if you start it up and hit the FX

00:29:14.600 --> 00:29:19.180
button I believe that it will apply-

00:29:19.180 --> 00:29:20.180
[pause]

00:29:20.180 --> 00:29:21.180
&gt;&gt;Ian: K.

00:29:21.180 --> 00:29:24.070
&gt;&gt;Reto: Let's have a look.

00:29:24.070 --> 00:29:28.570
&gt;&gt;Ian: Alright, let's see this is coloring
or-

00:29:28.570 --> 00:29:30.299
&gt;&gt;Reto: Branding effects.

00:29:30.299 --> 00:29:31.460
&gt;&gt;Ian: Alright.

00:29:31.460 --> 00:29:33.190
Oh here, vignette.

00:29:33.190 --> 00:29:34.920
Vignette's always good.

00:29:34.920 --> 00:29:36.010
There it is.

00:29:36.010 --> 00:29:45.160
&gt;&gt;Reto: Yeah, there you go, so they're applying
that in real time, you can see that on the

00:29:45.160 --> 00:29:46.160
edge there.

00:29:46.160 --> 00:29:47.160
&gt;&gt;Ian: Right.

00:29:47.160 --> 00:29:50.850
But, you'll notice that a lot of the effects
that you want are actually disabled in the

00:29:50.850 --> 00:29:51.850
real time mode.

00:29:51.850 --> 00:29:53.440
&gt;&gt;Reto: In the real time mode, yeah.

00:29:53.440 --> 00:29:55.270
&gt;&gt;Ian: Yeah, which isn't surprising.

00:29:55.270 --> 00:30:00.340
It's actually, in ICS we improved things,
in Jelly Bean we improved them even more,

00:30:00.340 --> 00:30:06.580
I think there's one extra step that the GL
team is talking about.

00:30:06.580 --> 00:30:14.070
But we've systematically been reducing the
number of operations that it takes to do a

00:30:14.070 --> 00:30:16.240
live preview with effects.

00:30:16.240 --> 00:30:22.890
So, originally it was extremely tedious and
you had to bring things through Java.

00:30:22.890 --> 00:30:23.890
&gt;&gt;Reto: Mmhmm.

00:30:23.890 --> 00:30:31.940
&gt;&gt;Ian: Now there's a single copy involved
if you're doing the GPU acceleration on your

00:30:31.940 --> 00:30:32.940
effects.

00:30:32.940 --> 00:30:33.940
&gt;&gt;Reto: Mmhmm.

00:30:33.940 --> 00:30:37.630
&gt;&gt;Ian: And in the future at some point, we
don't know exactly when, but the team thinks

00:30:37.630 --> 00:30:39.570
that they can get that down to zero copies.

00:30:39.570 --> 00:30:45.760
So, you'll be able to go directly from the
camera to the GPU to whatever without passing

00:30:45.760 --> 00:30:47.560
through user mode code at all.

00:30:47.560 --> 00:30:48.560
&gt;&gt;Reto: Yeah, that's excellent.

00:30:48.560 --> 00:30:49.560
&gt;&gt;Ian: Yeah.

00:30:49.560 --> 00:30:52.250
&gt;&gt;Reto: In fact, the app which I've seen which
really does the most intensive real-time effects

00:30:52.250 --> 00:30:53.250
is I think Paper Camera?

00:30:53.250 --> 00:30:54.330
They do a pretty good job of this.

00:30:54.330 --> 00:30:55.330
&gt;&gt;Ian: Yeah, they really do.

00:30:55.330 --> 00:30:58.260
&gt;&gt;Reto: they have quite most of their effects
at runtime which is kinda nice.

00:30:58.260 --> 00:31:01.270
&gt;&gt;Ian: Yep, and they've done a lot of work
to make that successful.

00:31:01.270 --> 00:31:02.820
&gt;&gt;Reto: I'm not surprised.

00:31:02.820 --> 00:31:06.840
So that's basically the way this app works
and it's got all of the standard filters that

00:31:06.840 --> 00:31:11.340
you'd expect and you can apply them to photos
either from the camera or from your gallery

00:31:11.340 --> 00:31:12.540
as well which is nice.

00:31:12.540 --> 00:31:18.679
There's no sort of community picture viewing
sharing functionality built in, at least not

00:31:18.679 --> 00:31:19.679
that I could find.

00:31:19.679 --> 00:31:23.350
&gt;&gt;Ian: That's a shame because the share intent
is really really easy to do and it works well

00:31:23.350 --> 00:31:24.350
for photos.

00:31:24.350 --> 00:31:25.929
&gt;&gt;Reto: Well share they've got, so they've
got the standard share intent.

00:31:25.929 --> 00:31:28.810
&gt;&gt;Ian: Oh OK, so you're just saying that they
don't hook into a-

00:31:28.810 --> 00:31:29.810
&gt;&gt;Reto: Exactly.

00:31:29.810 --> 00:31:30.810
&gt;&gt;Ian: -like a Flickr client.

00:31:30.810 --> 00:31:32.950
&gt;&gt;Reto: Like I start it up for the first time
and I can't flick through and look at other

00:31:32.950 --> 00:31:35.250
photos that people have taken and shared and
that sort of thing.

00:31:35.250 --> 00:31:37.880
Which makes a app like Instagram a big part
of that.

00:31:37.880 --> 00:31:40.900
&gt;&gt;Ian: I'm kinda on the fence about that.

00:31:40.900 --> 00:31:41.900
&gt;&gt;Reto: Really?

00:31:41.900 --> 00:31:44.830
&gt;&gt;Ian: Because on the one hand I'm like, yeah,
you're right, every time I pick up an app

00:31:44.830 --> 00:31:46.350
like it's really cool.

00:31:46.350 --> 00:31:51.179
On the other hand I'm like well, gee, don't
I have social networks for that?

00:31:51.179 --> 00:31:53.050
&gt;&gt;Reto: Yeah, it's true it's true.

00:31:53.050 --> 00:31:57.679
But you know, I kinda like the combination
particularly if it's not- if the community

00:31:57.679 --> 00:32:01.850
is really simplified, so it's not about anything
other than taking a photo and letting other

00:32:01.850 --> 00:32:02.850
people see it.

00:32:02.850 --> 00:32:03.850
&gt;&gt;Ian: Yeah.

00:32:03.850 --> 00:32:07.880
&gt;&gt;Reto: Cause then you kinda get that experience
of being able to interact and share with people

00:32:07.880 --> 00:32:11.900
who, you know, are using the same app, taking
the same sorts of photos, I think it adds

00:32:11.900 --> 00:32:12.900
something to it.

00:32:12.900 --> 00:32:13.900
&gt;&gt;Ian: I think you're right.

00:32:13.900 --> 00:32:14.990
&gt;&gt;Reto: OK, cool.

00:32:14.990 --> 00:32:18.710
So that's- now see and again we're hiding
the status bar.

00:32:18.710 --> 00:32:19.910
Please stop hiding the status bar.

00:32:19.910 --> 00:32:20.910
&gt;&gt;Ian: Yeah.

00:32:20.910 --> 00:32:21.910
&gt;&gt;Reto: I beg you.

00:32:21.910 --> 00:32:24.500
&gt;&gt;Ian: Just make sure you have a way to get
back, that's so important.

00:32:24.500 --> 00:32:25.500
&gt;&gt;Reto: Yeah, absolutely.

00:32:25.500 --> 00:32:29.850
&gt;&gt;Ian: Because here's the thing, let's say
I am completely immersed in your app and let's

00:32:29.850 --> 00:32:36.950
say I'm also an adult with responsibilities,
if I can get back to the status bar I can

00:32:36.950 --> 00:32:41.030
find out what time it is, I can respond to
a notification, I can check my calendar, I

00:32:41.030 --> 00:32:43.040
can do all these things.

00:32:43.040 --> 00:32:49.230
If not, then I have to leave your app anytime
my phone beeps, which is annoying.

00:32:49.230 --> 00:32:50.230
&gt;&gt;Reto: Yeah, absolutely.

00:32:50.230 --> 00:32:52.750
&gt;&gt;Ian: Because some notifications I literally
do not care about-

00:32:52.750 --> 00:32:53.750
&gt;&gt;Reto: No.

00:32:53.750 --> 00:32:55.340
&gt;&gt;Ian: -but I don’t know until I've looked
at the status bar.

00:32:55.340 --> 00:32:56.340
&gt;&gt;Reto: That's right.

00:32:56.340 --> 00:32:58.419
And you know, if you're doing a show like
this you need to know what time it is to see

00:32:58.419 --> 00:33:00.230
if you're massively over time.

00:33:00.230 --> 00:33:01.230
Which we always are.

00:33:01.230 --> 00:33:02.230
&gt;&gt;Ian: We're not.

00:33:02.230 --> 00:33:05.442
&gt;&gt;Reto: But at least we're not actually past
the end time of our show yet, which is, which

00:33:05.442 --> 00:33:06.442
is nice.

00:33:06.442 --> 00:33:07.442
&gt;&gt;Ian: That's quite true.

00:33:07.442 --> 00:33:08.442
&gt;&gt;Reto: So let's have a look.

00:33:08.442 --> 00:33:09.442
So we've had-

00:33:09.442 --> 00:33:12.330
&gt;&gt;Ian: I've been actively sabotaging the show
as we go on, you're carefully-

00:33:12.330 --> 00:33:13.330
&gt;&gt;Reto: [unintelligible]

00:33:13.330 --> 00:33:14.330
&gt;&gt;Ian: Yeah, OK, let's talk about-

00:33:14.330 --> 00:33:15.330
&gt;&gt;Reto: We've both been sabotaging.

00:33:15.330 --> 00:33:16.960
&gt;&gt;Ian: -what are the prescriptions for apps?

00:33:16.960 --> 00:33:17.960
&gt;&gt;Reto: Indeed.

00:33:17.960 --> 00:33:21.611
So these are the things we're looking for
having browsed through a bunch of these apps.

00:33:21.611 --> 00:33:23.540
The things that we've found which makes them
good.

00:33:23.540 --> 00:33:28.520
You know, we always say that you can't contradict
the design guide and that certainly still

00:33:28.520 --> 00:33:33.000
holds here but I think one additional thing
that we want to note is that it should really

00:33:33.000 --> 00:33:34.440
look good.

00:33:34.440 --> 00:33:39.800
These are apps which are targeted at people
who like the way things look; photographers,

00:33:39.800 --> 00:33:40.960
design folks, hipsters.

00:33:40.960 --> 00:33:46.140
It's really important that you create something
that's immediately appealing and you can see

00:33:46.140 --> 00:33:49.741
that at the beginning when I showed you the
feature graphics, and I meant to point it

00:33:49.741 --> 00:33:51.600
out at the time but completely forgot to.

00:33:51.600 --> 00:33:54.460
They all have feature graphics; they're all
really compelling-

00:33:54.460 --> 00:33:55.980
&gt;&gt;Ian: Yeah, really really pretty.

00:33:55.980 --> 00:33:58.620
&gt;&gt;Reto: -highly saturated images which look
great.

00:33:58.620 --> 00:34:02.950
And so that's the same sort of thing you want
here, you want to make sure the entire process

00:34:02.950 --> 00:34:04.730
is appealing.

00:34:04.730 --> 00:34:10.129
Similarly you want to make sure that the app
works on every image in the gallery and at

00:34:10.129 --> 00:34:12.049
the same time works on devices without the
camera.

00:34:12.049 --> 00:34:19.030
So for most of these apps, they allow you
to add effects both to live photos on the

00:34:19.030 --> 00:34:20.639
camera and to things you already have on your
phone.

00:34:20.639 --> 00:34:26.159
And so I want that to work on anything I can
pick from the Picasa gallery or from the phone

00:34:26.159 --> 00:34:27.159
gallery.

00:34:27.159 --> 00:34:31.029
And similarly I want it to work on my Galaxy
Nexus, I'm sorry on my Nexus 7, even though

00:34:31.029 --> 00:34:35.550
it has no rear facing camera, I'm not going
to use it to take photos but I have all of

00:34:35.550 --> 00:34:40.399
my Picasa gallery images synced to it, so
maybe I want to apply all these filters on

00:34:40.399 --> 00:34:41.399
a bigger screen.

00:34:41.399 --> 00:34:42.440
It should let me do that.

00:34:42.440 --> 00:34:44.669
&gt;&gt;Ian: Or you wanna just browse your friends'
photos.

00:34:44.669 --> 00:34:45.669
&gt;&gt;Reto: Exactly.

00:34:45.669 --> 00:34:48.109
[unintelligible]
&gt;&gt;Ian: That's actually one of the biggest

00:34:48.109 --> 00:34:54.929
problems that we had when we introduced Nexus
7 was photography apps that just assumed that

00:34:54.929 --> 00:34:58.049
if you didn't have a camera you wouldn't be
interested in a photo app and that's just

00:34:58.049 --> 00:34:59.049
not true.

00:34:59.049 --> 00:35:00.049
&gt;&gt;Reto: Exactly.

00:35:00.049 --> 00:35:03.180
And obviously you want to have the standard
and some unique hipster filters which I think

00:35:03.180 --> 00:35:06.740
most of the apps which we looked at today,
actually managed to do.

00:35:06.740 --> 00:35:13.079
&gt;&gt;Ian: To me, it's not just about hipster
filters, it's about ways to make the photo

00:35:13.079 --> 00:35:14.079
look good.

00:35:14.079 --> 00:35:18.599
So even if you have really unique filters,
one thing that I think the most successful

00:35:18.599 --> 00:35:25.900
apps do is a little bit of automatic tweaking,
behind the scenes, maybe even without telling

00:35:25.900 --> 00:35:26.900
the user.

00:35:26.900 --> 00:35:31.369
So maybe just a little bit of auto level balance,
auto white balance to try and make the photos

00:35:31.369 --> 00:35:32.369
look good.

00:35:32.369 --> 00:35:34.700
&gt;&gt;Reto: Absolutely, I mean that's the thing
we all know that we're not expecting to be

00:35:34.700 --> 00:35:38.329
able to take great photos with our camera
phones off the bat.

00:35:38.329 --> 00:35:41.590
It's not an SLR, you can't tweak all of your
manual settings and get it just so.

00:35:41.590 --> 00:35:47.140
So you're looking to concentrate on making
sure you're getting a good shot, good angles,

00:35:47.140 --> 00:35:48.380
good framing and all that sort of stuff.

00:35:48.380 --> 00:35:52.309
And then having the software help you make
it look like something that really represents

00:35:52.309 --> 00:35:53.309
it well.

00:35:53.309 --> 00:35:54.309
&gt;&gt;Ian: Absolutely.

00:35:54.309 --> 00:35:55.640
&gt;&gt;Reto: So let's give you some tips.

00:35:55.640 --> 00:36:00.170
The first tip here is on using the camera,
so you've got two options here which we saw

00:36:00.170 --> 00:36:05.839
both of which is either an app which uses
a completely custom UI which is what Camera

00:36:05.839 --> 00:36:14.930
ZOOM FX have done here so you get that completely
custom camera user interface which I can't

00:36:14.930 --> 00:36:15.930
find.

00:36:15.930 --> 00:36:21.930
Let's see, save and close, again save button,
so here you've got the completely custom camera

00:36:21.930 --> 00:36:23.329
user interface.

00:36:23.329 --> 00:36:25.660
And I think the first app that we looked at,
Eyeme-

00:36:25.660 --> 00:36:32.260
&gt;&gt;Ian: By the way, I think that where we're
seeing save, the correct verbiage to use is

00:36:32.260 --> 00:36:33.260
done.

00:36:33.260 --> 00:36:37.390
That's not a verb, but that's the label you
should be using.

00:36:37.390 --> 00:36:43.250
Because there is a case for having this intermediate-
like we've talked about this with alarm apps.

00:36:43.250 --> 00:36:48.451
There is an intermediate stage where you are
working on something and you don’t really

00:36:48.451 --> 00:36:49.559
feel complete.

00:36:49.559 --> 00:36:53.069
You don’t feel- like when I'm setting my
alarm I'm doing the hours, I haven't done

00:36:53.069 --> 00:36:54.069
the minutes yet.

00:36:54.069 --> 00:36:58.890
If it just- if I got a phone call then and
my alarm got saved in that state, that would

00:36:58.890 --> 00:36:59.910
not make me happy.

00:36:59.910 --> 00:37:00.910
&gt;&gt;Reto: Yeah.

00:37:00.910 --> 00:37:06.339
&gt;&gt;Ian: Likewise when I'm applying filters
and doing a lot of tweaking, you want to have

00:37:06.339 --> 00:37:10.400
sort of a commit step but you shouldn't call
it save.

00:37:10.400 --> 00:37:11.400
&gt;&gt;Reto: No.

00:37:11.400 --> 00:37:12.400
&gt;&gt;Ian: Cause that doesn't make any sense.

00:37:12.400 --> 00:37:13.400
&gt;&gt;Reto: Yeah.

00:37:13.400 --> 00:37:14.619
&gt;&gt;Ian: You should be saving as you go along.

00:37:14.619 --> 00:37:15.619
&gt;&gt;Reto: Absolutely.

00:37:15.619 --> 00:37:19.640
&gt;&gt;Ian: Because even though the user hasn't
committed they still don’t want to lose

00:37:19.640 --> 00:37:24.980
work, but you do want to get to a point where
you can roll back essentially.

00:37:24.980 --> 00:37:28.910
&gt;&gt;Reto: Yeah, particularly when you're applying
filters like this it's all logical operations,

00:37:28.910 --> 00:37:29.910
it's all maths right?

00:37:29.910 --> 00:37:30.910
&gt;&gt;Ian: Right.

00:37:30.910 --> 00:37:33.720
&gt;&gt;Reto: So while you don’t want to have
to keep each of those operations for every

00:37:33.720 --> 00:37:35.470
photo, once you're done, you're done.

00:37:35.470 --> 00:37:39.370
But in terms of being able to save your progress
even before you permanently alter the image,

00:37:39.370 --> 00:37:43.309
you can just keep a track of exactly which
effects, which filters have been applied,

00:37:43.309 --> 00:37:47.480
save that and then you can always reapply
it if they come back to the app after your

00:37:47.480 --> 00:37:48.480
process has been killed.

00:37:48.480 --> 00:37:52.609
&gt;&gt;Ian: Right, so you should always be prepared
for interruptions even interruptions that

00:37:52.609 --> 00:37:54.769
happen at a very inconvenient time for you.

00:37:54.769 --> 00:37:55.849
&gt;&gt;Reto: Absolutely.

00:37:55.849 --> 00:38:03.460
&gt;&gt;Ian: But you should never ask the user to
manage storage, to do anything but commit

00:38:03.460 --> 00:38:05.150
an action that's already in progress.

00:38:05.150 --> 00:38:08.849
&gt;&gt;Reto: Anytime you want to surprise a user
is with delight, not with annoyance.

00:38:08.849 --> 00:38:09.849
&gt;&gt;Ian: Absolutely.

00:38:09.849 --> 00:38:17.170
&gt;&gt;Reto: So this is Eyeme and you can see that
when you hit the camera button it goes to

00:38:17.170 --> 00:38:18.720
the basically to the built in camera.

00:38:18.720 --> 00:38:23.000
So this using all of the functionality that
you would have on the standard built camera

00:38:23.000 --> 00:38:30.099
app and then you can take a photo and then
it lets you retake or cancel or whatever you

00:38:30.099 --> 00:38:31.099
want to do.

00:38:31.099 --> 00:38:36.690
So that's your two approaches and both of
those described in the link down there in

00:38:36.690 --> 00:38:39.809
the camera topic of the Android developer
guides.

00:38:39.809 --> 00:38:42.599
So they will tell you how to use both approaches.

00:38:42.599 --> 00:38:47.720
Let's have a look, so the other thing we talked
about what conforming to the design guide.

00:38:47.720 --> 00:38:52.329
And so again we kind of have a few different
approaches here with these apps and I think

00:38:52.329 --> 00:38:58.550
they've pretty much all, except for Glimmr
done some form of sort of custom user interface.

00:38:58.550 --> 00:38:59.550
&gt;&gt;Ian: Yep.

00:38:59.550 --> 00:39:03.650
&gt;&gt;Reto: And I think that's alright in this
circumstance it kinda makes sense.

00:39:03.650 --> 00:39:07.970
When you have a particular ethos, a design
ethos which you want to be consistent with

00:39:07.970 --> 00:39:12.890
on these apps, there were a few little bits
and pieces that- Eyeme I think is my favorite

00:39:12.890 --> 00:39:16.480
look and feel in that it feels the most consistent
the most strongly branded.

00:39:16.480 --> 00:39:20.380
And they've done a decent job, they need to
get rid of the legacy menu button down here,

00:39:20.380 --> 00:39:23.859
they need to make the draw conform to our
new guidelines.

00:39:23.859 --> 00:39:27.819
The search here you should probably be using
the- so this is a little weird here where

00:39:27.819 --> 00:39:29.650
it goes off into its own search.

00:39:29.650 --> 00:39:31.720
This should really just be using a standard
action bar search.

